## {{ rule.title }}

When you are a U.S. citizen and a German tax resident, U.S.-source dividends are taxed by the U.S. (under § 1) and by Germany (under [§ 32d Abs. 1 EStG](https://www.gesetze-im-internet.de/estg/__32d.html)). The U.S.-Germany income tax treaty ([DBA-USA Article 10](https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-trty/germtech.pdf)) caps Germany's source-country share at 15 %. Because Germany doesn't actually withhold the U.S. side, IRS Publication 514's *treaty re-sourcing* worksheet provides an additional U.S. foreign tax credit equal to the German tax you actually paid on those dividends, capped by the U.S. tax above the 15 % treaty floor.

For 2025:

- **U.S.-source dividends** ([Pub. 514](https://www.irs.gov/publications/p514) line 15): **{{ rule.inputs_by_key["us.treaty_resourcing.us_source_dividends_usd"].value | money(currency="USD") }}**
- **Excess U.S. tax above 15 % treaty floor** ([Pub. 514](https://www.irs.gov/publications/p514) line 18 / line 19): **{{ rule.inputs_by_key["us.treaty_resourcing.treaty_resourcing_us_limitation_usd"].value | money(currency="USD") }}**
- **Residual German tax on the same dividends** ([Pub. 514](https://www.irs.gov/publications/p514) line 20c): **{{ rule.inputs_by_key["us.treaty_resourcing.worksheet_line_20c_residual_residence_country_tax_usd"].value | money(currency="USD") }}**

[Pub. 514](https://www.irs.gov/publications/p514) **line 21** — `min(line 19, line 20c)`: **{{ rule.outputs[0].value | money(currency="USD") }}**.

The worksheet line 21 amount carries to **[Form 1116](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1116), line 12** as the treaty re-sourcing add-on. [Form 1116](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1116) line 33 then caps the final allowed credit at the remaining nonrefundable room: **{{ rule.outputs[1].value | money(currency="USD") }}**.

If both line 19 and line 20c are zero, the additional FTC is zero — typically because there are no U.S.-source dividends or because Germany's residence credit already absorbed its tax on them. Otherwise, the lesser excess is what the U.S. additional credit can recover.

